{{Infobox book | name = Beyond Selflessness: Reading Nietzsche's Genealogy | image = File:Beyond Selflessness.jpg | image_size = 200px | author = [[Christopher Janaway]] | country = | language = English | subject = [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | pub_date = 2007 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]]) | pages = 296 | isbn = 978-0199570850 | dewey = | congress = | oclc = }} '''''Beyond Selflessness: Reading Nietzsche's Genealogy''''' is a philosophical examination of the work of [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] in ''[[On the Genealogy of Morality]]'' (1887). The monograph was released by [[Christopher Janaway]] in 2007 as part of his series examining the work of Nietzsche.<ref name="amazon1">{{Cite book|title=Beyond Selflessness: Reading Nietzsche's Genealogy: Amazon.co.uk: Christopher Janaway: Books |publisher=Amazon.co.uk |date= |id= {{ASIN|019957085X|country=uk}} }}</ref>
==Summary==
{{Empty section|date=May 2014}}
==Critical reception== Paul Bishop believed Janaway dealt well with the [[Nazism]] roots present in Nietzsche's philosophy, although this as a premise to his work is often debated.<ref>http://nietzschecircle.com/Pdf/Beyondselflessness.pdf</ref> Paul Katsafanas believed that: 'It is an exceptionally clear work, full of valuable insights, helpful reconstructions of arguments, and intriguing readings of some of Nietzsche’s most important claims.' Katsafanas did raise some issues on the intrinsic details of Janaway's claims, including the tension between self-affirmation and self-satisfaction, although concluded: 'Although I have expressed concerns about the details of some of Janaway’s arguments, the book as a whole is exceptionally rewarding'.<ref>http://people.bu.edu/pkatsa/janawayreview.pdf</ref>
