{{For|the NY watercolor society founded in 1890|New York Watercolor Club}} The '''New York Watercolor Society''', also known as the '''New York Water Color Society''', was a "short-lived" organization founded in 1850 by in part by [[John William Hill]]. It led to the founding of the [[American Watercolor Society]] in 1866.<ref name=Grove>{{cite book|author=Joan M. Marter|title=The Grove Encyclopedia of American Art|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sPGdBxzaWj0C&pg=RA4-PA507|year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-533579-8|page=507}}</ref>
==History== It was an early watercolor organization, following the 1804 establishment of the first Watercolor Society in England called the Society of Painters in Water Colours, the present day renamed [[Royal Watercolour Society]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Adelheid M. Gealt|title=Looking at art: a visitor's guide to museum collections|year=1983|publisher=R.R. Bowker|isbn=978-0-8352-1730-9|page=382}}</ref>
The name of the organization was sometimes confused with the [[New York Watercolor Club]]. For instance [[Childe Hassam]] was said to be the Society's first president (1889),<ref name="Sammarco2011">{{cite book|author=Anthony Mitchell Sammarco|title=Dorchester: A Compendium|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KwiR6OTYjXcC&pg=PA52|date=January 2011|publisher=The History Press|isbn=978-1-60949-217-5|pages=52–53}}</ref> but he was the first president of the New York Watercolor Club.<ref name="O'Sullivan p. 224">{{cite book|author1=Niamh O'Sullivan|author2=Aloysius O'Kelly|title=Aloysius O'Kelly: Art, Nation, Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5K4W8kWtqnkC&pg=PA224|year=2010|publisher=Field Day Publications|isbn=978-0-946755-42-4|page=224}}</ref>
